    <h1 class="title">Debian Project Leader Debate, 2006</h1>

      <ol>
<li class="meta"><em>-!- Topic for #debian-dpl-debate: 2006 DPL Election Debate HERE TODAY at 22:30 UTC | Rules: <a href="http://tinyurl.com/hxl2g">http://tinyurl.com/hxl2g</a> | Discussion in #debian-dpl-discuss | Ensure Sanity: /ignore #debian-dpl-debate JOINS PARTS QUITS</em></li><li class="meta"><em>-!- Topic set by dondelelcaro [n=don@archimedes.ucr.edu] [Thu Mar 16 11:51:30 2006]</em></li><li class="meta"><em>-!- gravity [n=david@pool-141-157-184-73.bos.east.verizon.net] has joined #debian-dpl-debate</em></li><li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; Welcome everyone to the 2006 Debian Project Leader Debate</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; The debate this year will be split into three separate sections</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; the first will be a composed response, where the candidates will answer questions that you all have submitted</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; we will spend the first 30-45 minutes on this section, the candidates will have 6 minutes to compose a response.</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; we'll then take a break, during which I'll explain the second part.</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; if you want to know in advance how it all will work, see /topic, where the debate rules are explained.</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; we're currently awaiting a few of the candidates, so hang on just a second for them to arrive.</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; please feel free to discuss what is happening in the debate in -discuss; throughout the debate questions that you pose will be picked up by panelists</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; these questions will be used wherever possible.</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; today, Thaddeus H. Black, David Nusinow, Martin-&#201;ric Racine, and MJ Ray will be pulling questions from you</li>
<li class="meta"><em>-!- mode/#debian-dpl-debate [+v madduck] by ChanServ</em></li><li class="meta"><em>-!- mode/#debian-dpl-debate [-v madduck] by don_armstrong</em></li><li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; Ok; sorry about the delay there, just getting everyone situated</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; The first question which the candidates will have 6 minutes to respond to:</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; Why are you running for DPL this year?</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2100">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2100</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; I'm running for DPL this year because I think that's a good way to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; encourage Debian to prioritise the things listed in my platform: making</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; sure we're continually doing interesting stuff and that we're all aware</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; of it; making sure we keep new blood flowing through the project; and</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; making sure we don't leave thinking about how we do things until this</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; time next year.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; EOT: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2100">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2100</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2099">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2099</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; I'm running for DPL this year because Debian has some serious problems that I'm in a better position to help solve as DPL, rather than as a private developer.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; EOT: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2099">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2099</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: SteveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2101">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2101</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; I'm standing as DPL this year because I believe I can do a good job of leading Debian.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; I thought long and hard about standing last year, but left it too late. After the</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; election, several of my DD friends complained that I hadn't stood, as they wanted to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; vote for somebody they could trust. This year, I considered my options again and this</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; time I'm ready. I believe I can help improve Debian and make the project a more fun and</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; productive place for all of us.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; EOT: SteveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2101">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2101</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2102">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2102</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; I wrote in my platform:</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; "I was at FOSDEM this week-end, and someone told me that Lars Wirzenius (which</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; was also there) had denominated himself.  At this point, I was not comfortable</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; to vote for any of the remaining candidate, so I decided to take the matter in</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; my hands and nominated myself, when it was clear no one else was nominating</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; themself. However, I am not Lars, and I will not try to replace him."</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; EOT: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2102">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2102</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2103">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2103</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; I am running for DPL because I think Debian is a great project, and I want</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; to contribute my share to it. I like working on Debian, but at times, I</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; think communication could be much better. I'd like to work on those issues,</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; because we're a project of skilled people.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; I think I can contribute well to try to resolve those.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2103">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2103</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2104">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2104</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; I run for DPL this year because I would like to bring my talents of</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; good leadership, organisation and understanding of social groups to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; optimal use for Debian.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; I started working on DPL stuff last year already and would like to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; continue that during the next term, to carry over expertise and</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; knowledge.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Debian needs to change its culture to remain competitative and become</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; more purpose driven and friendly. I would like to help it doing that.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; With the DPL team that will support me in that I have very good</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; chances of accomplishing that.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2104">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2104</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; second question, again 6 minutes:</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; Do you feel that being DPL would drastically alter the work you already</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; do for Debian? How?</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; (I've given the candidates an extra minute on this question, because I originally mentioned that I would send them the questions to -candidates)</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2105">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2105</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; As DPL, I'd have a bigger hat on, and be better able to help conflicting parties come to agreement.  Apart from the added work of speaking to groups and holding press conferences, there wouldn't be too much other change; I'm already a fairly political animal.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; EOT: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2105">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2105</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2106">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2106</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; No, my work would not change very much. During the last term I served</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; on the DPL team already and know how things work and have faced some</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; of the problems we are also going to face this coming term.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; I feel I am well prepared and ready for the task.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2106">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2106</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: SteveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2107">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2107</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; I don't think that being DPL will _drastically_ alter the work I already do for Debian.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; It _will_ cause me to look for more help on some of the tasks I currently work on -</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; package maintenance and CD/DVD work, as I expect I may have less time to do those tasks</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; unadided. I still expect to be able to help on those tasks, regardless.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; EOT: SteveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2107">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2107</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2108">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2108</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; I don't believe this would dramatically alter my work for Debian; rather that it</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; would allow me a bit more flexibility in achieving the goals I just mentioned and</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; thus let me give them a higher priority than otherwise; so that instead of just</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; focussing on my niches, I could reasonably go to people and say "you're doing great</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; stuff that deserves to be announced (or better supported, or made more official, or</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; whatever)" and get that to happen -- and I think that sort of activity from the DPL and</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; the Debian leadership in general is needed.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2108">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2108</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2110">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2110</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; No, I'm already working on Debian in general, and not limiting myself to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; just my packages. Amongst others by being part of the current DPL team, but</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; also by contributing to release management and infrastructural tasks.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; But, being DPL will allow me to work on some core parts of Debian I</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; wouldn't otherwise easily be able to do. I'd like to work on enabling</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; others to work well on Debian, by motivating them, and working on</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; problematic friction points in the project.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; I don't think this will conflict, rather, those tasks (DPL and non-DPL)</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; will complement eachother.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; EOT: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2110">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2110</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2109">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2109</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; It would. This would certainly be a new challenge for me</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; since my involvement in Debian has been limited in scope.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; However, I always have an eye on the distribution as a</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; whole instead as a collection of part. This is something</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; important for a DPL.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2109">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2109</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; third question, again 6 minutes to respond:</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; There have been two expulsion procedures started now. Do you think</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; they were inapropriate or do you think they are a reflection of real</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; problems in the project?</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2113">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2113</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; I don't think the options are mutually exclusive -- I tend to think</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; expulsion was inappropriate, and the fact that it's being considered</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; is a reflection of real problems in the project. I think it was inappropriate</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; because it's too heavy-handed: expulsion should be a last resort, made only</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; after other more moderate attempts have been made to ease the conflict and</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; failed. I hope that over the next year we'll start exploring what ways work</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; and don't, so that we do have some alternatives other than "ignore the problem"</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; and "expel people until the problem stops".</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2113">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2113</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; next response</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2114">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2114</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; I think the first expulsion procedure, against Andrew Suffield, was inappropriate.  Since Sven Luther</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; has threatened me with physical harm in the past, I don't feel unbiased enough to comment on whether</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; his expulsion procedure is appropriate.  However I would like to note that Sven Luther was quite vocally</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt;  in support of all the other expulsion procedures that were initiated in the past.  Is he getting his</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; just desserts?</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; EOT: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2114">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2114</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; next response</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2115">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2115</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; The whole concept of removing developers by acclamation is inappropriate but</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; this is also a reflection of real problems in the project. The DPL has</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; not been very visible in the last months and the project has sufferred from a</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; lack of direction.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; EOT: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2115">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2115</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; next response</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2116">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2116</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; While the expulsion procedure was designed to kick people out of the</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; project, it is extremly hard to do it with the current process since</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; it requires a degree of unity within the project that we did not have</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; in a long time.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; It is however a tool to express in a convincing and somewhat</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; threatening way "We really have a problem with the way you</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; behave. Think about it. Hard."··</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Unfortunatly this tool is rather coarse and undifferentiated. We can</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; not yet say something like "We think you are a bully and would like</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; you to change, since we value you anyway."··</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; On the other hand, those people it was used on so far really had a</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; hard time to understand more sublime tones and criticism.··</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; To have SOME tool is however a good start.··</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; I think the debian community needs a way to communicate drastic</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; disapproval. The current expulsion process can in reality do only</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; that.  IF we want to work with formal processes we need both ways to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; express the degree of our disapproval better and also an effective way</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; to expell people from the project.··</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; It would be much better if our community managed to correct</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; behaviouristic missfits in a more immediatly and private manner</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; though, without bureaucratic means.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; The two expulsion were intended to remove disruptive people from</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; the project. It is important that Debian learns to handle those</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; cases in order to keep the working climate healthy and be able to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; focus on the work. I think both candiates needed such a strong</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; reminder that they should not cross the lines quite so often.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; ~</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; EOT: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2116">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2116</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; next response</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: SteveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2117">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2117</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; The expulsions are clearly a sign of problems in the project. I don't believe</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; that they are necessarily inappropriate, but starting expulsion proceedings</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; should be considered a last resort.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; The two expulsions that have been raised are both for social issues, which saddens</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; me. I really wish that we could get on together without some of the friction that</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; has characterised some recent discussions in the project. Maybe that makes me a</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; "teletubby" in some people's eyes, but I have a strong belief in good, hard</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; technical debate _without_ people falling into personal insults. Getting angry and</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; rude to each other helps none of us...</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; EOT: SteveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2117">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2117</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; next response</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2119">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2119</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; Expulsion is a very harsh measure to take, or even to consider. The fact</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; that the process has been initiated twice is already a bad sign on itself.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; I don't think the existance of such procedure is a problem. In any large</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; project, especially one with strict entrance measures, there should be a</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; way to also decide to reverse the entrance of someone if someone's</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; seriously harmful to the project, externally or internally. However,</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; mediation should really be happening beforehand, preferably with the DPL</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; involved, to see if the differences can be resolved via less extreme</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; measures. It's an ultimate action.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; About the two cases in question, I don't think we should judge on the</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; rightfulness of starting the procedure, but rather, whether I think they</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; should succeed. I was supportive of the first one, and don't know about the</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; second one, I've been talking with the involved parties, and will decide</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; later.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; EOT: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2119">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2119</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; next question, the candidates were asked this 2 minutes ago:</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; Q: Since every DPL for the last few years has failed to communicate regularly despite their best goodwill, do you think you'd do better?  If so,  how and why?</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; (this, unless I've totally lost count, is question #4)</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2120">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2120</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; I think Debian's leaders have had great communication in the past.  If people</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; have questions, they can email them in.  Providing regular reports is the</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; secretaries job.  I think Manoj deserves a raise, because he has done a great</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; job as project secretary.  Also, Martin Schulze Debian Weekly News has filled in</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; any communications gap that a DPL would otherwise fill.  No need to reinvent the</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; wheel when Martin Schulze is doing such a good job.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; EOT: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2120">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2120</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; next response</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2121">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2121</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; I think I will do better because I will have someone acting as "secretary"</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; making sure I do reports. Also I will report what I am doing instead of</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; what I have done.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; I don't think tbm failed to communicate, at least during his first term.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; EOT: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2121">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2121</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; next response</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2122">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2122</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Communicating regularly is very difficult, and not something that should</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; be underestimated. For me (eg, as release manager), the biggest problem</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; is finding something that I think is worth saying, because "No, we're not</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; ready to release yet for the same reasons as last time" isn't very fun, or</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; very motivating. I think the DPL has similar problems -- it's great to make</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; posts when exciting things get done, but when you're trying to solve difficult</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; ongoing problems, you often don't get that regularly.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; So my main answer is twofold: first, that thanks to the wonders of blogging,</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; there's plenty of opportunity to talk about things in a fun interesting way</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; even when they're not finished, or not important enough to warrant a mailing</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; list post; and second, I think communication should be something the entire</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; project does, so I'd rather focus on encouraging other developers to post interesting</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; tidbits regularly than worry about the DPL repeating DWN's job.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2122">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2122</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; next response</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2123">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2123</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; I will definitely do better. If elected, I'll reserve a fixed minimum</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; amount of time each week for DPL tasks, which include maintaining an</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; agenda, and amongst others outwards communication. After all, that's a main</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; point of my platform.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; Also, I'll be working together with a team of good communicators, who I'll</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; happily lend opportunities to speak about DPL-related issues whereever</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; possible. They could offload some of the more 'easy' tasks too, at times.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Additionally, the review moments are meant to be 4 points where there'll</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; be a summary report of all DPL ongoing issues, supplementing the per-issue</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; reports.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; EOT: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2123">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2123</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; next response</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2124">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2124</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Yes, I am quite sure I will do better. My team and i already started</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; the *open* work in a public IRC channel and we intent to have regular</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; meetings in the open, dealing with questions and issues that will come</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; up.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; I do hope that this new transparency and openness will help the</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; project to understand the office of DPL better and also give us much</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; more traction within the project when we need to initiate change.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Again it prooved very valueable to see last years communication</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; attempts and how they worked out ... or failed to do so, in order to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; be able to make the right adjustments to the way we work.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; EOT: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2124">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2124</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; next response</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: steveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2125">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2125</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Communication from the DPL has been a bugbear for several years. Several DPLs</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; have faithfully promised to improve this, and true to form the candidates this</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; year have done the same.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; I believe I can do better, but then of course I _would_ say that :-)</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; I have a track record of keeping status reports going once I commit to them,</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; e.g. the monthly treasurer reports for debian-uk. There are 2 keys: finding the</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; time and being prepared to admit nothing has visibly happened. I believe I can</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; do both.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: steveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2125">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2125</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; question #5, again 6 minutes:</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; Over the years, we have seen a sad trend:  Whoever gets elected as</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; a DPL is a prominent, active member of the community.  The new DPL then</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; acts as he is expected for a couple of months, but soon thereafter the</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; interest seems to wear down, and we end up losing a valuable</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; contributor.  Why do you think this happens?  We know you don't have a</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; crystal ball, but do you think this will happen to you?  How will you</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; avoid it?</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; we'll ask one more of these questions, then take a 5 minute break</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; to answer a request, I'll try to make a pause between responses where possible</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Ari Pollak URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2126">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2126</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; That wouldn't be a problem for me because I'm neither a prominent nor an active member of the community.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; EOT: Ari Pollak URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2126">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2126</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2127">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2127</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; I think DPL's suddenly go silent because they run up against the true ruling</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; powers in Debian.  Unlike most of the previous DPL's, I was there on IRC when</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; the gutting of the DPL office was being discussed and implemented.  Martin</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; Michlmayr in his blog only recently stated what I have known for years.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; However, that can all change.  The DPL office may have been defanged, but it</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; still has claws, if a developer has been in the project long enough and knows</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; how things work and why things have been done the way they are.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; EOT: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2127">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2127</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: SteveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2129">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2129</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; There's nothing specific about the DPL post here. Debian has a history of causing</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; burnout in people performing lots of its key tasks. Constantly finding time to do</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; tasks that are often quite thankless can be difficult for the best of us, and I'd</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; be lying if I said I don't expect it to be an issue.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Setting aside a guaranteed minimum amount of time each week to do DPL work will help;</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; equally, so will setting aside some personal time where I will _not_ do DPL work</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; excepting emergency.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Also, I don't have much of a life to intrude... *grin*</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: SteveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2129">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2129</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2130">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2130</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; This does not entireley reflect my experience with previous DPL, so I cannot</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; explain a phenomena I did not observe myself.  My plan to avid this is to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; involve sufficient people so I do not get burn out</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2130">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2130</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2131">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2131</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; Being in any highly visible part of Debian puts you in a position</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; where you can get worn down pretty quickly, simply because there</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; are so many people who want good things out of Debian, because</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; they all have their own ideas, and any conflict in those ideas gets</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; brought to bear on the visible folks. I've been involved at that level</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; for a fair while now, and I think I'll be able to put up with it for a</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; year as DPL without getting flustered by it.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; EOT: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2131">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2131</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2132">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2132</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; This is a phenomenon that I had the opportunity to watch from near by</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; twice in a row: once with Martin and then again with Branden.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; I assume that people suffer from the tension that they want to change</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; things and despite their best effords dont manage, since they run</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; against barriers that they did not expect, or at least not in this</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; form or strength.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; In Brandens case there were also private miss-happs which we can only</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; hope that they wont come uppon us.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; Empowering the team around me early on would at least make sure that i</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; can be run over by trucks etc without leaving the project in that kind</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; of dilemma again.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2132">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2132</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2133">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2133</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; Anyway, I don't think that the trend is really there, Bdale and Martin</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; Michlmayr are at least still active, Bdale even as DPL team member.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Anyway, I will keep treating Debian work as fun. During the past year, I've</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; seen some difficult issues take away a lot of energy from the DPL team. I</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; will do my best to ensure that the upcoming year will still be fun to work</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; on some core areas in Debian.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; I haven't myself worn down from a year's worth of DPL team issues, and</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; I'm confident I won't let this happen this time either. A positive view</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; brings you far, and I believe I have such positive view.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; EOT: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2133">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2133</a></li>
