<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; How would you enforce a policy of documenting every role and project timetable in Debian, to enable easy staff changes for every task?</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; (or if not enforce, encourage)</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; we're going to give an extra 2 minutes to this question, because it was phrased suboptimally</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; (my bad)</li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; ================================================================================</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2136">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2136</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; I simply would not enforce/encourage such a policy. In my oppinion</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; debian is a lot about grassroots movements and people voting by</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; working on something they like.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; I would try to reglement as little as possible. We have enough</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; bureaucratic rules, we need less, not more.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; EOT: AndreasSchuldei URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2136">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2136</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; ================================================================================</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2138">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2138</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; Err, I wouldn't. I think that would be a waste of time</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; and detract from productive work on improving the distro.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Areas that benefit from being documented can be without any</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; enforcement required. I don't think any great encouragement</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; is needed -- if people want to do that, they already can, and</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; usually already do. I'm happy to suggest ways of talking to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; people cooperatively if they want explanations of how things work,</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; so that it doesn't turn into "but if I tell you anything, you're</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; just going to use it against me if I get busy later" or similar.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; EOT: Anthony Towns URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2138">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2138</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; ================================================================================</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2134">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2134</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; I wouldn't.  I don't believe organizational charts are possible or practical in</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; a large, ever-evolving volunteer project like Debian.  I think we should make a</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; best effort, but not sweat it.  As long as the powerful positions like ftp</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; master, new maintainer, people with root access and db access are documented and</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; accountable, everyone else can get their stuff documented on an as-needed basis.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; EOT: Ted Walther URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2134">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2134</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; ================================================================================</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: SteveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2139">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2139</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Enforcing documentation of roles and timetables is a little hard - we're volunteers!</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; But certainly each of the teams should be encouraged to do this; I've often found in</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; my own work that I don't truly understand something until I've tried to explain it</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; to others.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Part 1 of the task is to talk to each of the people involved right now, and try to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; get an honest assessment of what the roles entail and how things are proceeding.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Part 2 is to actually try to get these things documented well enough that others</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; in the project can understand them more readily. If help is needed on that</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; documentation, I will try and find people to help. If no help is forthcoming, I</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; will even pitch in myself.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; EOT: SteveMcIntyre URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2139">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2139</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; ================================================================================</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2140">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2140</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; I don't think this is raisonnable, let alone possible. New role and project</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; get created litteraly every days. Some process could be better documented,</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; but enforcing such a policy would be similar to rejecting every packages that</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; does not include its full specification.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; However I think it is a task "observers" might play a positive role,</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; observers being people loking at a task without actively working on it.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; EOT: Bill Allombert URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2140">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2140</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; ================================================================================</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Ari Pollak URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2143">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2143</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; I'm sure we could easily have a wiki page linking to the various project sites, but keeping track of every minute project change in a central place really doesn't sound like it would work. On a side note, major project timetable/membership changes should be added to Debian Weekly News.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; EOT: Ari Pollak URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2143">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2143</a></li>
<li class="n10"> &lt;<b>@don_armstrong</b>&gt; ================================================================================</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; Begin Reponse: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2144">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2144</a></li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; I would simply work on the documention part myself, or with others if they</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; volunteer. I already know a great deal about the various teams, and could</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; pretty easily find out more that I need to know.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; About staff changes, we're not a company. We are a project consisting of</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; volunteers, volunteers who you don't just reassign at the snap of your</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; fingers. I don't think there's any need to do that, either, but if there's</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; percieved or real problems with a task, I'll look into it. I don't think</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; it's ever a good idea to 'change' staff, but rather, to encourage teams to</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; reinforce themselves with new members when the need arises, possibly</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; starting out with trainees (such as release-assistants with limited</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; privileges). By increasing transparancy, it is much easier also for new</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+f|</b>&gt; people to get involved and prove themselves.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+b|</b>&gt; .</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+c|</b>&gt; People should generally only stop doing a task when they no longer are</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+d|</b>&gt; interested in it.</li>
<li class="n1"> &lt;<b>+e|</b>&gt; EOT: Jeroen van Wolffelaar URL: <a href="http://channels.debian.net/paste/2144">http://channels.debian.net/paste/2144</a></li>
